<section xml:id="S_gcd">
  <title>The Greatest Common Divisor</title>
  <introduction>
    <exploration xml:id="PA_gcd">
      <title>The Greatest Common Divisor</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Explain what it means to say that a nonzero integer <m>m</m> divides an integer <m>n</m>.
            Recall that we use the notation
            <m>m \mid n</m> to indicate that the nonzero integer <m>m</m> divides the integer <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> be integers with <m>m \ne 0</m>.
            Explain what it means to say that <m>m</m> does not divide <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <definition xml:id="gcd">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers, not both 0.
            A <term>common divisor</term>
                <idx><h>common divisor</h></idx>
            of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is any nonzero integer that divides both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            The <term>largest</term> natural number that divides both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is called the
            <term>greatest common divisor</term>
                <idx><h>greatest common divisor</h></idx>
            of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            The greatest common divisor of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is denoted by <m>\gcd \left( {a, b} \right)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="PA_gcd1">
          <p>
            Use the roster method to list the elements of the set that contains all the natural numbers that are divisors of 48.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="PA_gcd2">
          <p>
            Use the roster method to list the elements of the set that contains all the natural numbers that are divisors of 84.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Determine the intersection of the two sets in Parts<nbsp/><xref ref="PA_gcd1"/> and<nbsp/><xref ref="PA_gcd2"/>.
            This set contains all the natural numbers that are common divisors of 48 and 84.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="PA_gcd4">
          <p>
            What is the greatest common divisor of 48 and 84?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="PA_gcd5">
          <p>
            Use the method suggested in Parts<nbsp/><xref ref="PA_gcd1"/> through<nbsp/><xref ref="PA_gcd4"/> to determine each of the following:
            <m>\gcd( {8, - 12})</m>, <m>\gcd( {0, 5} )</m>,
            <m>\gcd( {8, 27} )</m>, and <m>\gcd( {14, 28})</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are integers,
            make a conjecture about how the common divisors of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are related to the greatest common divisor of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exploration>
