  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>The System of Integers</title>
    <p>
      Number theory is a study of the system of integers,
          <idx><h>integers</h><h>system</h></idx>
      which consists of the set of integers,
      <m>\mathbb{Z} = \left\{ {\, \ldots , - 3, - 2, - 1, 0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots \, } \right\}</m> and the various properties of this set under the usual operations of addition and multiplication and under the usual ordering relation of
      <q>less than.</q>
      The properties of the integers in <xref ref="Ta_axiomsforintegers"></xref>
      will be considered axioms in this text.
    </p>
    <p>
      We will also assume the properties of the integers shown in <xref ref="Ta_propertiesofintegers"></xref>.
      These properties can be proven from the properties in <xref ref="Ta_axiomsforintegers"></xref>.
      (However, we will not do so here.)
    </p>
    <table xml:id="Ta_axiomsforintegers">
      <title>Axioms for the Integers</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell></cell>
          <cell>For all integers <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>:</cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Closure Properties for Addition and Multiplication</cell>
          <cell><m>a + b \in \mathbb{Z}</m> and
            <m>ab \in \mathbb{Z}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Commutative Properties for Addition and Multiplication</cell>
          <cell><m>a + b = b + a</m>, and
            <m>ab = ba</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Associative Properties for Addition and Multiplication</cell>
          <cell><m>\left( {a + b} \right) + c = a + \left( {b + c} \right)</m> and
            <m>\left( {ab} \right)c = a\left( {bc} \right)</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Distributive Properties of Multiplication over Addition</cell>
          <cell><m>a\left( {b + c} \right) = ab + ac</m>, and
            <m>\left( {b + c} \right)a = ba + ca</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Additive and Multiplicative Identity Properties</cell>
          <cell><m>a + 0 = 0 + a = a</m>, and
            <m>a \cdot 1 = 1 \cdot a = a</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Additive Inverse Property</cell>
          <cell><m>a + \left( { - a} \right) = \left( { - a} \right) + a = 0</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <table xml:id="Ta_propertiesofintegers">
      <title>Properties of the Integers</title>
      <tabular>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Zero Property of Multiplication</cell>
          <cell>If  <m>a \in \mathbb{Z}</m>, then  <m>a \cdot 0 = 0 \cdot a = 0</m>.</cell>
        </row>
        <row bottom="minor">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Cancellation Properties</cell>
          <cell>If  <m>a, b, c \in \mathbb{Z}</m> and
